issue.title: Update Dependencies to Latest Version
issue.body:
Update composer dependencies in the repository to eliminate any unnecessary security vulnerabilities.

This is in relation to Igor's report, and Dependabot security Alerts:

https://github.com/bcgov/digital-journeys/security/dependabot

I think we have two main options to resolve at least the majority of these issues. Some vulnerabilities likely do not yet have a fix available, so may need to be mitigated in other ways.

1. Delete package-lock.json from the repository
      a) This is my preference, and what we have done for the Moodle project
      b) Every published code change (or automated build) will always download the latest (minor) updates
          i) This allows for automated patches on a regular basis
          ii) Introduces risk that a code change could have greater / unexpected impacts in other areas
              1) Automated functional testing is recommended to reduce this risk
2. Have developers update composer files locally, test / validate functionality, then deploy the updated package-lock.json via Git to the repo
       a) This would require a GitHub issue to be created (for each update / release)
       b) Could be triggered by alerts (Dependabot, etc.)
       c) Could be set based on time / resourcing
             i) Once per sprint
             ii) Every code change / deployment
             iii) Weekly, monthly, etc.
        d) This allows for the most control, but also takes the most time / resources
        e) The risk with this approach is that once active development slows or ceases, updates may be neglected

I think the logical first step is to delete or update the package-lock.json file to see how many vulnerabilities we can clear up with a quick update / deployment.

Either option is very easy to run in dev and revert if there are any issues.

issue.title: Address EOL Python for AWS ECFs
issue.body:
**Describe the issue**

We are contacting you as we have identified that your AWS Account currently has one or more Lambda functions using Python 3.6 runtime.

We are ending support for Python 3.6 in AWS Lambda. This follows Python 3.6 End-Of-Life (EOL) reached on December 23, 2021 [1].


**Additional context**
- AWS email May 18 in Julian's mailbox

**Definition of done**
- "We recommend that you upgrade your existing Python 3.6 functions to Python 3.9 before August 17, 2022."
